Norwegian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305072831/http://lista.vg.no/liste/topp-20-single/1/dato/1999/periode/skoleslutt|archive-date=March 5, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Romania (Romanian Top 100)<ref name=\"rt100\"/>\n|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Spain (PROMUSICAE)<ref name=\"spain\"/>\n|13\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Sweden (Sverigetopplistan)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19990001 |title=\u00c5rslista Singlar - \u00c5r 1999 |publisher=GLF |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |language=Swedish |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722003533/http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19990001 |archivedate=July 22, 2015 }}</ref>\n|12\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Switzerland (Schweizer Hitparade)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swisscharts.com/charts/jahreshitparade/1999|title=Swiss Year-end Charts 1999|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|18\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/assets/files/yearly%20best%20selling%20singles.pdf |title=Yearly Best Selling Singles 1999 |publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=February 9, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018142431/http://www.bpi.co.uk/assets/files/yearly%20best%20selling%20singles.pdf |archivedate=October 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|10\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Adult Top 40 (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|14\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Dance Maxi-Singles Sales (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Latin Songs (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Latin Pop Songs (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|2\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Mainstream Top 40 (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Tropical Airplay (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|8\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (1990\u201399)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|UK Singles (Official Charts Company)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukchartsplus.co.uk/|title=Official Singles Chart 1990\u201399|accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n|51\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref name=\"usend\"/>\n|38\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications and sales==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|certyear=2013|relyear=1999|artist=Ricky Martin|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|award=Platinum|number=2|type=single}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Belgium|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=1999}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snepmusique.com/les-disques-dor/?awards_cat=64&awards_awd=0&awards_year=0&awards_artist=Ricky+martin&awards_title=&awards_edit_distrib=&awards_sort=date_certif-desc&awards_nb=30&submitAdvanced=Search |title=SNEP Certifications Ricky Martin|language=French |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]] |accessdate=February 11, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925060529/http://www.snepmusique.com/fr/page-259165.xml?year=1999 |archivedate=September 25, 2012 }}</ref>|salesamount= 161,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Ventes_Chansons_Tout_Temps.php?debut=2700|title=Les Meilleures Ventes \"Tout Temps\" de 45 T. / Singles / T\u00e9l\u00e9chargement|publisher=InfoDisc|accessdate=February 11, 2016}}</ref>|certyear=1999|relyear=1999}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|title=Livin' La Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|relmonth=1}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|artist=Ricky Martin|title=Livin' La Vida Loca|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=2019|accessdate=October 14, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=New Zealand|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=1999|recent=website|id=1043}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Norway|title=Livin' la Vida Locaartist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1999|certyear=2000|certref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifpi.no/sok/lst_trofeer_sok.asp?type=artist |title=IFPI Norsk platebransje |publisher=IFPI Norway |language=Norwegian |accessdate=February 11, 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725054452/http://www.ifpi.no/sok/lst_trofeer_sok.asp?type=artist |archivedate=July 25, 2012 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Sweden|relyear=1999|certyear=1999|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Gold}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|title=Livin' La Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|award=Platinum|certyear=1999|id=3936-2798-1|salesamount=900,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-1999-ricky-martin-livin-la-vida-loca__4817/|title=Official Charts Flashback 1999: Ricky Martin \u2013 Livin' La Vida Loca|last=Myers|first=Justin|date=July 11, 2014|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref>|relyear=1999|accessdate=September 3, 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|title=Livin' la Vida Loca|artist=Ricky Martin|type=single|relyear=1999|certyear=1999|award=Platinum|salesamount=1,100,000 <small>([[CD single|physical]])</small><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sA0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA63|title=Best-Selling Records of 1999|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=BPI Communications Inc.|date=January 22, 2000|accessdate=June 4, 2015|page=63|issn=0006-2510|volume=112|number=4}}</ref><div>502,000 <small>([[Music download|digital]])</small>|salesref=<ref name=digital/>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* The 2000 album ''La Vida Mickey'' features modern versions of Spanish songs with the voices of the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] characters in the background singing along.\n* Country music parodist [[Cledus T. Judd]] recorded a cover titled \"Livin' Like John Travolta\" for his 1999 album ''[[Juddmental]]''.\n* Japanese singer [[Hiromi Go]] remade the song as \"Goldfinger '99\". [[Masaki Sumitani]] (Razor Ramon H.G., who refers to it as \"the song that I used without permission\") uses this as his theme song, to which he thrusts his crotch at the beginning of each episode. A parody of this version is made into a music video in the \"Hiromi Go\" episode of ''Hard Gay''.\n* The [[Toy Dolls]], a British punk rock band, recorded a version of the song on their 2000 ''[[Anniversary Anthems]]'' album.\n* Ten Masked Men, a British death metal band, covered this song on the 2000 album ''Return of the Ten Masked Men''.\n* In November 2000, [[ApologetiX]] (That Christian Parody Band) released ''[[Spoofernatural]]'', including a parody of this song, \"Livin' What Jesus Spoke of\".\n* An uptempo cover remix by [[CJ Crew]] feat. Giorgio for the 2000 ''[[Dancemania]]'' compilation ''[[Dancemania Speed|Speed 4]]'' was later included on ''[[Dancemania Speed Best 2001]]''.\n* [[El Vez]] covered this song on his 2001 album ''Boxing with God''.\n* [[New york City]] radio station [[WPLJ]] did a parody of this song in 2001 titled \"Livin' la Vida Choka\".\n* ''Dave Ryan in the Morning'' from [[St. Paul, Minnesota]] radio station [[KDWB]] did a cover titled \"Livin' in Minnesota\".\n* A eurobeat cover by Italian singer [[Dave Rodgers]], \"Livin' La Vida Mickey\", was recorded for ''[[Eurobeat Disney 3]]''.\n* In 2002, Serbian rock band [[Night Shift (band)|Night Shift]] covered the song on their debut album ''[[Undercovers (Night Shift album)|Undercovers]]''.\n* A version of the song performed by [[Eddie Murphy]] and [[Antonio Banderas]] is played at the end of the 2004 movie ''[[Shrek 2]]''. It also appears on its [[Shrek 2 (soundtrack)|soundtrack]].\n{{col-2}}\n* A version of the song performed by Blue Day appears on their 2004 album ''Shaka Rock''.\n* A children's version called \"Drinkin' a Coca Cola\" was recorded for the [[Chuck E. Cheese's]] soundtrack.\n* The song was parodied as \"Livin' la Vida Yoda\" by the Bitter Tasting Omelette, which is a group made up of brothers Todd and Gavin Downing.\n* [[Jimmy Fallon]] parody the song as \"Livin' la Vida Yoda\", a reference to ''[[Star Wars]]'' character [[Yoda]], on an episode of ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' which was coincidentally the same one that Martin performed the song as the musical guest.\n* [[Shlock Rock]], a group that parodies popular music with a Jewish theme, wrote \"Learning to Dance the Hora\".\n* Knockout Theory, a New Jersey punk rock band, often performs a version of the song at their live shows.\n* ''Nashville Star'' contestant Gabe Garcia sang a country version of the song in 2008.\n* English metalcore band [[Bury Tomorrow]] released their cover onto Myspace on September 9, 2010.\n* Christian singer [[Mark Lowry]] parodied this song as \"Livin' For Deep-fried [Okra]\". A video of the parody\u2014fairly resembling the original Martin video\u2014was presented at his New York City concert event \"Mark Lowry on Broadway\" at the Beacon Theatre.\n* Draumurinn did a cover in Icelandic in January 2011, called \"Fari\u00f0 er allt til fjandans\".\n* Runner up contestant of ''[[Superstar K3]]'' [[Busker Busker]] sings a cover of the song in their unique style in the top 9 round.\n* During the 2013 [[ESPN]] Nine for IX film, ''The 99ers'', composed almost entirely of home video footage recorded by U.S. Women's Soccer Team Member, Julie Foudy, some of the other members of the team can be heard singing along to the song at one point during the movie.\n* Filipino rock singer [[Kean Cipriano]] covered the song for his final impersonation in ''[[Your Face Sounds Familiar (Philippines season 2)|Your Face Sounds Familiar]]''.\n* A version by the satirical [[Capitol Steps]] had a Bill Clinton imitator singing \"Since the wife's away/ I'm livin' la vida loca\".\n* In 2017, the Ukrainian club project \"#SiSiKe4\" made its remix for this song, which is called \"Ricky Martin - Livin' la Vida Loca (#SiSiKe4 Remix)\"\n* In 2019, Japanese singer [[Koda Kumi]] covered the song on July 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7lEdMdb95Xs|title=\u5016\u7530\u4f86\u672a / Livin' La Vida Loca|work=YouTube|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref> She would cover Hiromi Go's remake \"Goldfinger '99\" (retitled \"[[Goldfinger 2019]]\") less than a month later on August 13, which became her fourth of nine planned singles for the year. \n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[List of Adult Top 40 number-one songs of the 1990s]]\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 1999]]\n*[[List of Billboard Mainstream Top 40 number-one songs of the 1990s]]\n*[[List of Billboard Rhythmic number-one songs of the 1990s]]\n*[[List of number-one Billboard Hot Latin Tracks of 1999]]\n*[[List of number-one Billboard Latin Pop Airplay songs of 1999]]\n*[[List of number-one singles from the 1990s (New Zealand)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1999 (Canada)]]\n*[[List of number-one singles of 1999 (Ireland)]]\n*[[List of RPM number-one dance singles of 1999]]\n*[[List of UK Singles Chart number ones of the 1990s]]\n*[[List of Romanian Top 100 number ones of the 2000s]]\n*[[RPM Year-End]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|ricky-martin|livin-la-vida-loca}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Ricky Martin singles}}\n\n[[Category:1999 songs]]\n[[Category:1999 singles]]\n[[Category:Ricky Martin songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Spanglish songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Adult Top 40 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot Latin Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Canadian Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one dance singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Greece]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Hungary]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Romania]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Desmond Child]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Wayne Isham]]\n[[Category:RPM Adult Contemporary number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Draco Rosa]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Luis G\u00f3mez Escolar]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Desmond Child]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Livin%27_la_Vida_Loca"}
{"title_page": "Joe Lycett", "text_new": "{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{short description|English comedian}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image         = LycettPascoeGreen290518-11 (42449359001) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Boss performing in 2018\n| name          = Hugo Boss\n| birth_name    = Joe Harry Lycett\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1988|7|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality   = British\n| height        = \n| medium        = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[Television comedy|television]], [[Entrepreneur]]\n| genre         =\n| subject       =\n| active        = 2009\u2013present\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Manchester]]\n| signature     = Hugo Boss signature.png\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.joelycett.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Hugo Boss''' (born '''Joe Harry Lycett'''; 5 July 1988), known professionally as '''Joe Lycett''', <ref>{{cite web |url=https://instagram.com/p/4xSyFyv1-d/ |title=A happy birthday to the centre of my pavlova @joelycett |first=Aisling |last=Bea |authorlink=Aisling Bea |website=[[Instagram]] |date=5 July 2015}}</ref> is a British comedian. He has appeared on TV shows including ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'', ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[QI]]'', as the announcer on Saturday [[BBC One]] show ''[[Epic Win]]'', the narrator for [[Ibiza Weekender]] and as the presenter on [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]'' and [[Channel 4]]'s consumer show, ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2020, he announced that he had changed his legal name by [[deed poll]] to Hugo Boss in protest against the [[Hugo Boss|company of the same name]] sending cease-and-desist letters to small businesses and charities that use the word Boss.<ref name=\"HugoBBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51703859|title=Joe Lycett: Comedian changes his name to Hugo Boss|publisher=BBC|date=2 March 2020|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n[[File:Joe_Lycett_(comedian_-_Equality_Network).PNG|thumb|Boss performing for the [[Equality Network]]'s ''LGBT Rights: Stand-up for Russia'' event in [[Edinburgh]], August 2013]]\nBoss was the 2009 [[Chortle Student Comedian of the Year]], the winner of Bath New Act competition in 2009, the runner-up in the 2009 [[Laughing Horse New Act of the Year]], and a finalist in the 2011 [[BBC New Comedy Awards]]. In 2012, his debut stand-up show ''Some Lycett Hot'' was nominated for the Best Newcomer at the [[Edinburgh Comedy Awards]].\n\nBoss has appeared on television on ''Live At The Apollo'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'', ''[[Celebrity Juice]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[Spicks and Specks (2014 TV series)|Spicks and Specks]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie to You?]]'', ''[[Insert Name Here]]'' and ''[[Virtually Famous]]'', and was a regular panellist on the ''[[E4 (TV channel)|E4]]'' show ''Dirty Digest''. He has also co-written narration on [[ITV2]] shows ''[[The Magaluf Weekender]]'' and ''[[Ibiza Weekender]]''. Boss featured on ''[[Alan Davies: As Yet Untitled]]'' Christmas Special with [[Jason Manford]], [[Richard Coles|Rev Richard Coles]] and [[Jo Joyner]]. Boss also starred as one of the contestants in the fourth series of ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]''. Recently Boss has made several guest appearances on ''[[Sunday Brunch]]'' in the absence of one of the regular hosts.\n\nIn 2002 Boss appeared in series 2 of ''[[Two Pints of Lager and a Packet of Crisps]]'' when he played [[Bungle (Rainbow)|Bungle]] in the episode where Jonny Keogh hired the character from ''[[Rainbow (TV series)|Rainbow]]'' and a bouncy castle with his \u00a31,000 scratch card winnings.<ref>Parsnips, Buttered: How to win at modern life, one email at a time {{ISBN|1473640415}}</ref>\n\nOn the radio he has been a guest on [[Scott Mills]], [[Greg James]] and [[Nick Grimshaw]]'s programmes on [[BBC Radio 1]] and on [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]]'s programme on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. In August 2011 he wrote and performed the short story ''Spooky and the Van'' which was broadcast in the Afternoon Reading slot on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0144v1t |title=Afternoon Reading: Spooky and the Van |first=Joe |last=Lycett |website=BBC Radio 4 |date=25 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2013 he made his debut on ''[[Just a Minute]]'' on BBC Radio 4. In September 2016 he took over from Miles Jupp as the host of ''[[It's Not What You Know (radio series)|It's Not What You Know]]'', also on BBC Radio 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=It's Not What You Know |website=BBC Radio 4 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b036wvkd}}</ref>\n\nBoss was also known as \"the resident news hound\" on [[Josh Widdicombe]]'s [[Radio X (United Kingdom)|XFM]] radio show, which was broadcast on Saturday (and later Sunday) mornings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |title=Joe Lycett |website=[[The Dome Leisure Centre|The Dome]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105061206/http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his appearances on various radio stations, Boss has also featured as a guest on numerous podcasts, including ''[[My Dad Wrote a Porno]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acast.com/mydadwroteaporno/footnotes-joe-lycett|title=Footnotes: Joe Lycett \u2013 My Dad Wrote A Porno on acast|first=|last=acast|date=21 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> ''SoundCheck Podcast,''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |title=Glastonbury Special With Joe Lycett |access-date=3 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303110900/https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |archive-date=3 March 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> ''[[The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/podcasts/comedians_comedian_podcast/episode_168_joe_lycett/ |title=Episode 168 \u2013 Joe Lycett (Live) \u2013 The Comedian's Comedian Podcast with Stuart Goldsmith |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> and the Richard Herring Leicester Square Theatre Podcast.\n\nOn 12 February 2019 Hugo Boss took over as the new presenter<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a26321575/the-great-british-sewing-bee-new-host-joe-lycett/|title=The Great British Sewing Bee viewers give their verdict on new host Joe Lycett: Joe has stepped into Claudia Winkleman\u2019s shoes |date=13 February 2019 |newspaper=Good Housekeeping |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> on [[The Great British Sewing Bee#Series 5 (2019)|the fifth series]] of [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]''.\n\nBoss started presenting his consumer show;  ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back,'' branded as a 'sexy [[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'<ref>{{Citation|title=15: John Hannah, Kevin McCloud and Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/6TSUouTkJZXxZfbwsdalF9|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> with help from various guests and Mark Silcox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/video/2019/04/05/42701/mark_silcox_vs_burger_king|title=Mark Silcox vs Burger King : Video 2019 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|last=Solutions|first=Powder Blue Internet Business|website=www.chortle.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The show takes on big corporations, such as airlines and banks, to provide justice for consumers, with a comedic spin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back/on-demand/67621-001|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back \u2013 On Demand|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second series.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|date=1 March 2020|work=The Independent|access-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2019 and 26 October 2019, Boss stood in for [[Rylan Clark-Neal]] on 'Rylan on Saturday' on [[BBC Radio 2]]. In December 2019 he returned to Radio 2 covering [[Sara Cox]]'s drivetime show during the [[Christmas]] and [[New Year]] period.\n\n==Personal life==\nBoss was born in [[Hall Green]], Birmingham. His parents are David and Helen Lycett.  He attended [[King Edward VI Five Ways]] grammar school, studied Drama and English at the [[University of Manchester]], and was awarded the [[Chortle Awards#2009|2009]] [[Chortle Awards|Chortle]] Student Comedian of the Year. Boss frequently refers to his [[bisexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://attitude.co.uk/article/comedian-joe-lycett-being-bisexual-has-its-own-challenges/7495/ |title=Comedian Joe Lycett:'Being Bisexual Has Its Own Challenges |date=26 June 2015 |newspaper=Attitude |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> and [[pansexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/ive-always-distaste-authority-joe-lycett-comedy-revenge-pansexuality/ |title=Joe Lycett on comedy, revenge and pansexuality |date=19 October 2016 |newspaper=iNews |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> as part of his [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up]] routines.\n\nIn 2015, while performing in [[York]], Boss was given a parking ticket for parking illegally in a [[taxi rank]]. The ensuing trail of correspondence, between him and [[City of York Council]], was recounted as an anecdote on ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'' and then became the basis for one of his stand-up routines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkmix.com/comedian-dreams-up-genius-way-to-dodge-york-parking-fine-celebrates-with-street-party/ |title=Comedian dreams up genius way to dodge York parking fine \u2013 celebrates with street party |date=6 November 2015 |website=YorkMix |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Boss got [[Lord Mayor of Birmingham|Birmingham Lord Mayor]] [[Yvonne Mosquito]] to officially open his kitchen extension. At first Mosquito declined, as it was not a public event, but after Boss raffled four tickets to the event to the public she agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-england-birmingham-48276732/lord-mayor-opens-joe-lycett-s-new-kitchen-extension|title=The lord mayor, a comedian and a kitchen|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, he changed his name by [[deed poll]] from Joe Lycett to Hugo Boss stating he was drawing attention to fashion company [[Hugo Boss]]'s use of legal action against [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|small businesses]].<ref name=\"HugoBBC\"/> The company has claimed a number of firms have been violating its copyright through the use of the word Boss.<ref>{{cite news|URL=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|work=[[The Independent]]|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|first=Jacob|last=Stolworthy|date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ List of television performances\n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Epic Win'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| August \u2013 September 2011\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Dirty Digest''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| November 2011\n|-\n| 2012\n